    "narrative": "For today\u2019s slate, **Mickey Moniak** (75.75) and **Seiya Suzuki** (73.90) headline our offense, offering the highest efficiency scores against favorable matchups. **Mickey Moniak** benefits immensely from a platoon advantage against a high-xERA arm and a prime #2 hole in the order, while **Seiya Suzuki** gains significant value from a slow-delivery pitcher that boosts his steal probability, a critical factor for our internal prioritization. Joining them in the \"Strong\" tier, **Austin Riley** (67.79) and **Vinnie Pasquantino** (67.69) are locked into the lineup; **Austin Riley** is buoyed by a significant park factor, and **Vinnie Pasquantino** leverages a robust platoon edge against a right-handed starter. **Corbin Carroll** (64.33) remains an automatic start despite a tough stolen base environment, as his high base projection ensures he provides value even when the battery is difficult to run on.\n\nThe most difficult decision on the bench was **Cole Young** (44.59), who remained on the outside looking in despite a decent floor. While **Cole Young** provides intriguing utility, his projected efficiency fell short of the middle-infield options currently rostered, such as **Travis Bazzana** (55.81), whose combination of park and platoon advantages made him the superior play for the MI slot. Regarding risk, we are monitoring the matchup for **Tyler Soderstrom** (48.75), whose score is suppressed by a unfavorable platoon split against a left-handed starter; we are keeping him active only because our alternatives are currently thin or injured. Owners should note that **Giancarlo Stanton**, **Trevor Story**, and **Max Muncy** remain sidelined, and we continue to rotate depth pieces like **Brice Turang**, **Luis Campusano**, **Zach McKinstry**, **Kyle Karros**, and **Carson Williams** to manage our daily game caps effectively.",
